===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# An [[unexpected]] [[event]] with [[negative]] [[consequences]] occurring without the [[intention]] of the one [[suffering]] the consequences.
#* '''c.1603''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''[[s:The Tragedy of Othello, The Moor of Venice|The Tragedy of Othello, The Moor of Venice]]'', I-iii,
#*: Wherein I spake of most disastrous chances, / Of moving '''accidents''' by flood and field{{...}}
#: {{ux|en|to die by an '''accident'''}}
# {{lb|en|transport|vehicle}} Especially, a collision or similar unintended [[event]] that causes [[damage]] or [[death]].
#: {{ux|en|There was a huge '''accident''' on I5 involving 15 automobiles.}}
#: {{ux|en|My insurance went up after the second '''accident''' in three months.}}
#* {{quote-magazine|year=2013|month=July-August|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/philip-j-bushnell Philip J. Bushnell]
|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2013/4/solvents-ethanol-car-crashes-amp-tolerance Solvents, Ethanol, Car Crashes & Tolerance]
|passage=Surprisingly, this analysis revealed that acute exposure to solvent vapors at concentrations below those associated with long-term effects appears to increase the risk of a fatal automobile '''accident'''. Furthermore, this increase in risk is comparable to the risk of death from leukemia after long-term exposure to benzene, another solvent, which has the well-known property of causing this type of cancer.}}
# Any chance event.
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[chance|Chance]].
#* '''c.1861-1863''', {{w|Richard Chevenix Trench}}, in 1888, ''Letters and memorials'', Volume 1,
#*: Thou cam'st not to thy place by '''accident''', / It is the very place God meant for thee;{{...}}
#* {{quote-journal|year=1991|month=Autumn|volume=60|issue=4|page=589|title=Montaigne|author=Robert M. Adams|journal=American Scholar|passage=And so with his writing, which he proudly said was a perfect counterpart of his life. '''Accident''' played a major part in both.}}
# Any property, [[fact]], or [[relation]] that is the result of chance or is [[nonessential]].
#* '''1883''', {{w|J. P. Mahaffy}}, ''Social life in Greece from Homer to Menander‎'',
#*: This '''accident''', as I call it, of Athens being situated some miles from the sea, which is rather the consequence of its being a very ancient site,{{...}}
#: {{ux|en|Beauty is an '''accident'''.}}
# {{lb|en|euphemistic}} An instance of [[incontinence]].
#* '''2009''', Marcia Stedron, ''My Roller Coaster Life as an Army Wife'', Xlibris Corporation, {{ISBN|1462817890}}, [http://books.google.de/books?id=by6CBEvNtWIC&lpg=PA56&pg=PA56&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false page 56]:
#*: We weren’t there long when Karin asked about our dog. When we told her Chris was in the car, she insisted we bring him up to the apartment. I rejected her offer and said he might have an '''accident''' on the carpet and I didn’t want to worry about it.
# {{lb|en|euphemistic}} An unintended [[pregnancy]].
# {{senseid|en|philosophy}} {{lb|en|philosophy|logic}} A quality or attribute in [[distinction]] from the [[substance]], as ''[[sweetness]]'', ''[[softness]]''.
#* '''1902''', William James, ''The Varieties of Religious Experience'', Folio Society 2008, page 171:
#*: If they went through their growth-crisis in other faiths and other countries, although the essence of the change would be the same{{...}}, its '''accidents''' would be different.
# {{lb|en|grammar}} A [[property]] attached to a word, but not [[essential]] to it, such as [[gender]], [[number]], or [[case]].
#* ''a'' '''1799''', John Parkhurst, ''A Hebrew and English lexicon without points'', page 25
#*: An adjective, so called because adjectitious, or added to a substantive, denotes some quality or '''accident''' of the substantive to which it is joined {{...}}
# {{lb|en|geology}} An irregular surface feature with no apparent cause.
# {{lb|en|heraldry}} A [[point]] or [[mark]] which may be [[retained]] or [[omitted]] in a [[coat of arms]].
# {{lb|en|legal}} [[casus]]; such [[unforeseen]], [[extraordinary]], [[extraneous]] [[interference]] as is out of the range of ordinary [[calculation]].
# {{lb|en|uncountable|philosophy|uncommon}} [[appearance|Appearance]], [[manifestation]].
#* '''14thC''', {{w|Geoffrey Chaucer}}, ''[[s:The Canterbury Tales/The Pardoner's Prologue and Tale|The Pardoner's Prologue and Tale]]'' in ''{{w|The Canterbury Tales}}'',
#*: These cookes how they stamp, and strain, and grind, / And turne substance into '''accident''', / To fulfill all thy likerous talent!
#* '''1677''', ''Heraclitus Christianus: or, the Man of Sorrow'', chapter 3, page 14:
#*: But as to Man, all the Fruits of the Earth, all sorts of Herbs, Plants and Roots, the Fishes of the Sea, and the Birds of the Air do not suffice him, but he must disguise, vary, and sophisticate, change the substance into '''accident''', that by such irritations as these, Nature might be provoked, and as it were necessitated.
#* {{quote-text|year=1989|author=Iysa A. Bello|title=The medieval Islamic controversy between philosophy and orthodoxy|page=55
|passage=Nonetheless, those who have no evidence of the impossibility of the transformation of '''accident''' into substance believe that it is death itself which will be actually transformed into a ram on the Day of Resurrection and then be slaughtered.}}
#* {{quote-text|year=2005|author=Muhammad Ali Khalidi|title=Medieval Islamic philosophical writings|page=175
|passage=It would also follow that God ought to be able to transmute genera, converting substance into '''accident''', knowledge into ability, black into white, and sound into smell, just as he can turn the inanimate into animate{{...}}}}
#* {{quote-text|year=2010|author=T. M. Rudavsky|title=Maimonides|page=142
|passage=nor can God effect the transmutation of substances (from '''accident''' into substance, or substance into '''accident''', or substance without '''accident''').}}

